    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nCurrently using severity names like `'ERROR'` / `'WARN'` / etc. is allowed and even [used in tests](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/d77808ec59be2428f03fc43489ec70dcb71ac572/test/functional/lua/diagnostic_spec.lua#L3380). Like `vim.diagnostic.config({ signs = { severity = { min = 'WARN', max = 'ERROR' } } })`.\n\nHowever, it is not entirely clear [from the documentation](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/d77808ec59be2428f03fc43489ec70dcb71ac572/runtime/doc/diagnostic.txt#L42-L67). *Technically* `vim.diagnostic.severity` does have `'ERROR'`/etc. as a value, but examples imply and only use `vim.diagnostic.severity.ERROR` approach.\n\nThe dedicated [type](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/d77808ec59be2428f03fc43489ec70dcb71ac572/runtime/lua/vim/diagnostic.lua#L391-L394) also seems to not allow string names. Although it is [explicitly supported](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/d77808ec59be2428f03fc43489ec70dcb71ac572/runtime/lua/vim/diagnostic.lua#L488-L499) without deprecation warnings.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nUsing severity names is clearly documented: either allowed+documented+typed or fully not allowed (which is a breaking change).",
    "closed_at": "2026-04-16T14:32:37Z",
    "closed_by": {
